accessibility.text: Hellas Planitia is a vast plain within the massive, circular impact basin Hellas, located in Mars' southern hemisphere. It is one of the largest known impact craters in the Solar System, with a floor 7,152 m (23,465 ft) deep and a diameter of about 2,300 km (1,400 mi). Centered at 42.4°S 70.5°E,

Hellas Planitia features the lowest point on Mars, is a known source of global dust storms, and may have contained lakes and glaciers. Formed during the Late Heavy Bombardment period, it spans the boundary between the Hellas and Noachis quadrangles.
